         <div type="commentary" subtype="frontmatter" xml:space="preserve"><p>The papyrus preserves parts of a single column containing 43 lines written in a small-sized informal hand, on the back of a letter. Only the right margin is partially preserved. The handwriting suggests a dating to the 2nd cent. AD, but the apostrophe used to separate double consonants may well date the text to the early 3rd cent. The text is organized into sections by headings in the form of a question: on such topic see  I. Andorlini, ‘Testi medici per la scuola: raccolte di definizioni e questionari nei papiri’, in A. Garzya, J. Jouanna (eds.), <emph rend="italics">Les Textes médicaux grecs: Tradition et ecdotique</emph> (Naples 1999) 7-15. Recently published parallels are GMP 1.6 (see also <listBibl><bibl><ref target="http://papyri.info/biblio/72008">Hanson 2003</ref></bibl></listBibl>), P.Strasb. gr. inv. 849 (ed. by <listBibl><bibl><ref target="http://papyri.info/biblio/73378">Magdelaine 2004</ref></bibl></listBibl>), and P.Oslo inv. 1576 (ed. by <listBibl><bibl><ref target="http://papyri.info/biblio/76019">Maravela-Solbakk and Leith 2007</ref></bibl></listBibl>). The question-headings, which are in <emph rend="italics">eisthesis</emph>, might have been accompanied by <emph rend="italics">paragraphus</emph> or <emph rend="italics">diple</emph>. Horizontal strokes mark the end of answers at ll. 20 and 32. The text is a sistematic exposition of surgery consisting in divisions into its ‘forms’ and also into different classes of surgical operations. Two sections can be distinguished ll. 1-20 and 21-42. Some parallels of concious systematizations of the branch of medecine can be found <emph rend="italics">e.g.</emph> in Mnesith.Ath. frr. 10-11 Bertier, Herophil. T42-49 von Staden, and Erasistr. fr. 32 Garofalo. The present text may derive from a form of introductory handbook on medicine, but the complexity of the divisions suggests a derivation from the introductory section of a book entirely devoted to surgery (see BKT III 22-26 and P.Oxy. III 437).</p></div>
