         <div type="commentary" subtype="linebyline">
            <list>
               <item corresp="#lb2" xml:space="preserve"><ref>1-20</ref> <p>That further unnamed forms are referred to at ll. 18-20 indicates that they were listed before each was explained individually in the surviving passage. To judge from parallel formulations, a total number of forms may also have been given at the beginning, and we can infer that this total would have come to at least nine (with the first, now lost, being introduced by in an initial μέν clause).</p></item>
               <item corresp="#lb3" xml:space="preserve"><ref>2</ref> <p>[μεθο]δικόν is clearly suggested by με̣θόδ[ου] at the end of the line (see ll. 16-18 for a parallel construction). This would presumably refer to the selection of a suitable procedure upon examination of the patient.</p></item>
               <item corresp="#lb4" xml:space="preserve"><ref>3-4</ref> <p>Between l. 3 and l. 4, there is a trace of an ascending diagonal above delta, but apparently too high to form part of a letter.</p></item>
               <item corresp="#lb12" xml:space="preserve"><ref>10-11</ref> <p>It is difficult to determine precisely the nature of the contrast between πλαγιοτομεῖν (‘cutting obliquely’) and λοξοτομεῖν (‘cutting at an angle’), unless of course they are meant as synonyms (see the three forms of incision described by Antillus <emph rend="italics">apud</emph> Aët. 3.15 [CMG 8.1, 274 Oliv.]).</p></item>
               <item corresp="#lb21" xml:space="preserve"><ref>18-9</ref> <p>There is insufficient space for both the article, which seems necessary, and another word before ὀνομάτων.</p></item>
               <item corresp="#lb27" xml:space="preserve"><ref>23</ref> <p>The unattested μεθορεύει, which could mean something like ‘to share boundaries with’, is probably an error. An emendation to μεθοδεύει (‘treats’-’cures’) is the simplest solution paleographically, but we are left without an obvious subject. The passive μεθοδεύεται would give the most satisfactory sense, i.e. ‘In how many ways are the affections in surgery treated?’.</p></item>
               <item corresp="#lb42" xml:space="preserve"><ref>35-42</ref> <p>The precise meaning of this passage on the compound ways remains somewhat obscure. σωτηρίαν (ll. 39-40) should be taken as the object of ἐπαγγείλεται. Although it would seem unnatural to separate it from δισσήν in this way at l.39, the phrase τῶν δισσὴν ἐχόντων can be read as referring back to ll. 35-36, with ἐπαγγελίαν subsequently left understood. At the end of l. 40, the traces might admit of a reading such as [α]ὕ̣τ̣η̣, giving perhaps e.g. [π]ροσάγεται̣ [γὰ]ρ̣ [α]ὕ̣τ̣η̣, but this is very unclear.</p></item>
            </list>
